Leptospirosis, dogs - USA (New York) 971112122006
[1
Date: Thu, 20 Apr 2000 08:31:57 -0500
From: Carole A. Bolin <cbolin@nadc.ars.usda.gov>

Leptospirosis is indeed a re-emerging disease of dogs in the United States.
It is important veterinarians be aware of the increased incidence and
various clinical syndromes caused by the various serovars of Leptospira.
However, the statements that dog to human transmission of leptospirosis is
rare should be qualified somewhat.
Before the widespread use of canine leptospiral vaccines in the United
States, dogs were a common source of exposure of humans to this agent. Dogs
infected with _Leptospira canicola_ remain a significant problem in many
parts of the world and have played a major epidemiological role in
outbreaks of human leptospirosis in Nicaragua and elsewhere.
Leptopspiral vaccines are still in wide use in dogs in the United States.
The vaccines provide reasonable levels of protection against the clinical
signs produced by leptospiral serovars _canicola_ and
_icterohaemorrhagiae_. However, the vaccines do not provide absolute
protection from infection and shedding of the organism.
There are reports in the literature of humans acquiring leptospirosis from
vaccinated dogs. Until recently, there have not been canine vaccines for
protection from serovars other than _canicola_ and _icterohaemorrhagiae_. A
new vaccine has been introduced which also contains serovars _pomona_ and
_grippotyphosa_. Vaccines are not yet available for protection of dogs from
serovar _bratislava_ infection.
The serovars most common in dogs in North America (i.e., _pomona_ and
_grippotyphosa_) are serovars prevalent in wildlife populations including
skunks, opossums, and raccoons. Rodents are not thought to be important
carriers of these serovars.
--
Carole Bolin, DVM, PhD
Research Leader
National Leptospirosis Reference Center
USDA, Agricultural Research Service
National Animal Disease Center
Ames, IA 50010
e-mail: cbolin@nadc.ars.usda.gov
