[2
Date: Thu, 20 Apr 2000 09:16:27 -0500
From: Christopher W. Olsen <olsenc@svm.vetmed.wisc.edu>

As regards the posting on leptospirosis in dogs in Massachusetts, I believe
it is very important to emphasize several points. First, as regards the
comment that "the disease can be transmitted from dogs to humans, but it is
a rare occurrence," it should be noted dogs are the most important source
of infection for people in the United States (see Mandel, Douglas and
Bennett's Principles and Practice of Infectious Disease, 1995, p. 2137).
Secondly, regarding the comment that "there are vaccines for leptospirosis,
but their efficacy is debatable," it is important to distinguish protection
from clinical disease versus protection from infection.
The Leptospira bacterins available for animals can decrease the
occurrence/severity of clinical disease, but do not prevent infection and
subclinical shedding of the organism. Thus, people coming into contact with
canine urine (dog owners, veterinarians, laboratory staff, etc.) should
always handle it as if it contains _Leptospira_ organisms.
Finally, as to the moderator's comment "leptospirosis has not been
available in dog vaccines for a year or more," this is simply not true. A
variety of Leptospira-containing bacterins for dogs are readily available
commercially, including vaccines that contain not only the traditional _L.
icterohaemorrhagiae_ and _L.canicola_ strains, but also the _L. pomona_ and
_L.grippotyphosa_ strains have emerged recently as a cause of acute renal
disease in dogs, as well as in people.
(See: Brown et al. 1996. JAVMA 209:1265-1267; Gerding et al. 1997.
Infection 25:379-380; Forrest et al. 1998. Veterinary Radiology and
Ultrasound 39:337- 340)
--
Christopher W. Olsen, DVM PhD
Assistant Professor of Public Health
School of Veterinary Medicine
University of Wisconsin-Madison
e-mail: olsenc@svm.vetmed.wisc.edu
